						Section 2 - Black: Book 7: Chapter 5: Verse 8
					-
						-
							When the gods had come to the end, their power and strength departed.
							They won them again by the Kroça (Saman), and that is why the Kroça has
							the name. In that they sing the Kroça at the end of the pit, they win
							power and strength at the end of the sacrifice. They sing the Sattra
							syarddhi (Saman) at the end of the Ahavaniya; verily, making Agni a
							witness, they advance to prosperity. They sing the Prajapater Hrdaya
							within the shed; verily they win his favour. They sing the Çloka
							(Saman) in front of the Sadas they place glory in themselves. Therefore
							one breath protects all the limbs. Therefore, just as a bird about to
							fly upwards raises its head aloft, so the sacrificers are highest among
							people. The Udgatr mounts a throne; verily they attain rule. The Hotr
							(mounts) a swing; verily they mount the back of the firmament. The
							Adhvaryu (mounts) two mats; verily they reach the surface of the ruddy
							one. So many indeed are the worlds, and in them in order they find
							support. Then the sacrificers make thus a bridge to mount, for the
							gaining of the world of heaven.
